assumptions and blind spots are complicit in US homelessness and contribute to the degree of suffering that homeless people face. At the same time, Small, Kordosky and Moore show us how our own sense of connection and compassion can bring us into touch with the actions that will lessen homelessness and bring greater humanity to the experience of those who remain homeless. The raw emotion of The Man in the Dog Park will forever change your appreciation for, and understanding of, a life so many deal with outside of the limelight of contemporary society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHomeless personszUnited States. 0aHomelessnesszUnited States. 4aAnthropology. 4aMemoir. 4aSocial Work. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  ahomelessness, homeless shelters, poverty, ethnography, affordable housing, stigma, veterans, compassion.1 aKordosky, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW0 cprintz978150174879040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501748806?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501748806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501748806/original  a978-3-11-069046-0  Cornell Univers